Gallio nard; for the spleen‚ with vinegar, pottage or fig. In vinegar it is an antidote to poisonous fungi, as also to mistletoe3 in wine, to hemlock, the poison of the shrew mouse, sea weever α and scorpions. It is a great aid to clear vision. With raisin wine it is applied to eye fluxes‚ and with honey to bruises. Ear trouble is cured by sumigation with the steam of the decoction, or when bloody pus exudes, by pounded wormwood with honey. Three or four twigs, with one root of Gallie nard and six cyathi of water, are diuretic and an emmenagogue3 it is specific for faulty menstruation if taken with honey orb applied as a pessary in wool. With honey and soda it is helpful for quinsy. In water it cures night rashes. Recent wounds it heals if applied before they have been touched with water3 it cures, more- over‚ sores on the head. With Cyprian wax or with fig it makes an exceptionally good application for affections of the flanks.⁶ It also cures pruritus, but must not be given to severish patients. Taken in drink on sea voyages it prevents nausea; worn under a belly-band‚ swellings of the groin.c It induces sleep if inhaled through the nose or placed secretly under the sufferer’s head. Put into clothes it keeps away moth. Rubbing the body all over with it in oil drives away gnats, as does the smoke of it when bui-nt. Writing ink mixed with the infusion protects the writing from mice. Ashes of worm- wood mixed with ointment and rose-oil stain the hair black.

XXIX. There is also a sea wormwood, called by some seriphum, the most approved growing at Taposiris in Egypt. At the ceremonies of Isis the priests carry a branch of it ritually before them.
